ype":"questionRevisions","id":"55825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent due to recurrent chest infections. He has experienced four episodes of pneumonia in the past year, each requiring antibiotic treatment. He also reports a persistent runny nose and cough. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals scattered crackles bilaterally. Otoscopic examination shows dull tympanic membranes bilaterally. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Immunodeficiency","Cystic fibrosis","Asthma","Kartagener syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and radiological findings in this case strongly suggest \u003Cstrong\u003EKartagener syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This rare, autosomal recessive condition is defined by a triad of situs inversus (evidenced here by dextrocardia), chronic sinusitis (indicated by the persistent runny nose and dull tympanic membranes), and bronchiectasis (suggested by recurrent respiratory infections).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E can manifest with recurrent respiratory infections and bronchiectasis. However, it typically involves pancreatic insufficiency and poor growth, which are not mentioned here. Furthermore, dextrocardia is not associated with cystic fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Easthma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause recurring respiratory symptoms, it rarely leads to recurrent pneumonia or bronchiectasis. The presence of dextrocardia also makes asthma an unlikely explanation for this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunodeficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can result in frequent infections, it would not account for the dextrocardia or chronic sinusitis. Moreover, the patient\u0027s up-to-date immunisations suggest a functional immune system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E (GORD) can occasionally cause respiratory symptoms, particularly in children. However, it would not explain the dextrocardia, chronic sinusitis, or the extent of respiratory involvement observed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKartagener syndrome is a variant of primary ciliary dyskinesia, a disorder characterised by structural or functional ciliary defects. This leads to impaired mucociliary clearance, resulting in recurrent sinopulmonary infections and eventual bronchiectasis. The situs inversus in Kartagener syndrome is believed to occur due to ciliary dysfunction during embryonic development. Diagnosis is typically confirmed through genetic testing, electron microscopy of ciliary ultrastructure, or ciliary function tests. Management involves aggressive treatment of infections, airway clearance techniques, and addressing complications as they arise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Kartagener syndrome is characterised by situs inversus, chronic sinusitis, and bronchiectasis.","Kartagener syndrome is a subset of primary ciliary dyskinesia, resulting from ciliary defects.","Children with Kartagener syndrome often present with recurrent respiratory infections."],"references":["Image: Nevit, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons. Available at: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0","Skeik N, Jabr FI. Kartagener syndrome. Int J Gen Med. 2011 Jan 12;4:41-3. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21403791/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14162"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21017"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21017"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/duPBzPIBIn9OtEqAYYOX2nKcvOu389.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/duPBzPIBIn9OtEqAYYOX2nKcvOu389.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1226,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:28:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:29:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6845"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55825"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"d